===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|la|rota|t=wheel}} + {{m|en|virus}}. The name was first proposed in July 1974 in an article in ''{{w|The Lancet}}''.<ref>{{cite-journal|date=1974-07-13|author={{w|Thomas Henry Flewett|Flewett, T. H.}}, Bryden, A. S., Davies, H., Woode, G. N., Bridger, J. C., Derrick, J. M.|title=Relation between viruses from acute gastroenteritis of children and newborn calves|journal={{w|The Lancet}}|volume=304|issue=7872|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(74)91631-6|page=63|passage=We propose therefore that these reovirus-like or orbivirus-like enteritis viruses of calves and children are in a group separate from both orbiviruses and reoviruses, and we suggest that the term “rotavirus” (from the Latin rota, a wheel) should be used for them.}}</ref>

